July 1558":"7 juli 1558","1501":"1501","1478":"1478","1497":"1497","1573":"1573","about 1499":"circa 1499","about 1497":"circa 1497","1549":"1549","Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England","Ashford, Devon, England":"Ashford, Devon, England","Burlescombe, Devon, England":"Burlescombe, Devon, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"en":{"about 1497–7 July 1558":"about 1497–7 July 1558","1492–1583":"1492–1583","1497–1558":"1497–1558","1501–1560":"1501–1560","1525–1573":"1525–1573","1478–1503":"1478–1503","1480–Female":"1480–Deceased","5 January 1503":"5 January 1503","1583":"1583","1560":"1560","1492":"1492","1480":"1480","1525":"1525","1503":"1503","1558":"1558","7 July 1558":"7 July 1558","1501":"1501","1478":"1478","1497":"1497","1573":"1573","about 1499":"about 1499","about 1497":"about 1497","1549":"1549","Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England","Ashford, Devon, England":"Ashford, Devon, England","Burlescombe, Devon, England":"Burlescombe, Devon, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tregarthen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Cornish: habitational name from Trevarthian (either Newlyn East or Saint Hilary, Cornwall). Both placenames derive from Middle Cornish <i>tref</i> ‘estate, farmstead’ + a personal name related to Old Welsh <i>Arthgen</i> (Middle Welsh <i>Arthen</i>)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":52,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":61,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Tregarthen was born about 1497, in Cornwall, England, her father, John Tregarthen, was 20 and her mother, Johanna Trethurffe, was 19. She had at least 1 daughter with George William Tanner. She died on 7 July 1558, in Ashford, Devon, England, at the age of 62, and was buried in Burlescombe, Devon, England."},"et":{"about 1497–7 July 1558":"umbes 1497–7. juuli 1558","1492–1583":"1492–1583","1497–1558":"1497–1558","1501–1560":"1501–1560","1525–1573":"1525–1573","1478–1503":"1478–1503","1480–Female":"1480–Surnud","5 January 1503":"5. jaanuar 1503","1583":"1583","1560":"1560","1492":"1492","1480":"1480","1525":"1525","1503":"1503","1558":"1558","7 July 1558":"7. juuli 1558","1501":"1501","1478":"1478","1497":"1497","1573":"1573","about 1499":"umbes 1499","about 1497":"umbes 1497","1549":"1549","Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Aslockton, Nottinghamshire, England","Ashford, Devon, England":"Ashford, Devon, England","Burlescombe, Devon, England":"Burlescombe, Devon, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"about 1497–7 July